  "prompt": "Can you get the flu even after vaccination?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to get the flu even after being vaccinated. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Vaccine effectiveness:\n- Flu vaccines are typically 40-60% effective in preventing illness\n- Effectiveness can vary depending on the match between vaccine strains and circulating viruses\n\n2. Reasons you might still get the flu:\n- The vaccine didn't create strong enough immunity\n- You were exposed to the flu before the vaccine took effect\n- You were infected with a flu strain not covered by the vaccine\n- Your immune system didn't respond well to the vaccine\n\n3. Important notes:\n- Even if you get the flu after vaccination, symptoms are often milder\n- The vaccine can reduce the risk of serious complications\n- Getting vaccinated is still recommended by health experts\n\n4. Best practices:\n- Get vaccinated annually\n- Practice good hygiene (handwashing, avoiding close contact with sick people)\n- Maintain a healthy lifestyle to support your immune system\n\nWhile the flu vaccine isn't 100% guaranteed to prevent illness, it significantly reduces your risk of getting the flu and experiencing severe symptoms.",
